Here’s what caught our attention on Monday: 1. Sasfin results Financial services provider, Sasfin is expected to release it results for the year ended June 30, 2018 on Monday. In a trading statement dated in early September, the company said it expects headline earnings per share to decrease between 41.69% and 36.69% to between 356.74 cents and 387.33 cents. Earnings per share is also expected to fall by 39.53% and 34.53% to 356. 74 cents and 387.33 cents. Update to follow. 2. Rhodes Food Group results Rhodes Food issued a trading update for the year ending September 30, 2018. The owner of Zing juice, Pakco and Magpie brands, says it expects earnings to be adversely impacted by the increased interest payments which are expected to be between R26 million and R28 million higher than the previous year as well as by the drought in the Western Cape. Headline earnings is expected to be 18% and 38% lower than the R237 million reported last year. Headline earnings per share is also expected to fall between 30% and 40% lower to 67.8 cents and 58.1 cents. Results are expected to be released on November 20, 2018. 3. Unions to sign gold sector wage deal Solidarity Union and the Association of Mineworkers and Construction Union (Amcu) will be signing a three-year gold sector wage deal with mining company, AngloGold Ashanti on Monday. The two unions, as well as UASA, have declared a dispute with several other mining companies, including Harmony Gold and Sibanye-Stillwater, after being at an impasse, Reuters reported. 4. Eskom running out of coal No fuel for the fire is the new situation weighing on power utility Eskom. The company told EE Publishers that it needs at least 1.3 million tons of coal per month to recover the required level of stock needed for the end of the current financial year, which ends on March 31, 2019. This poses a risk to supplies at at least four of its power stations which now have less than 10 days left of coal supplies. Read: The coal crisis at Eskom worsens 5. State capture inquiry lends ear to banks The state capture inquiry, will on Monday hear the banks’ side of the story. Representatives from South Africa’s major banks are expected to explain to the commission why they closed the  bank accounts belonging to the Gupta’s and their businesses back in 2016. The action later led to cabinet’s intervention in the matter. Update to follow.